GO Thin vs Early downregulated genes
This plot points to a coordinated reduction in core metabolic and energy‑producing pathways as cells move from the early biofilm stage into the thin biofilm state. 
Many of the enriched categories fall under carbohydrate metabolism, glycolysis, monocarboxylic acid metabolism, and alcohol and nucleotide catabolic processes, indicating that thin biofilm cells suppress the high‑flux carbon and nucleotide turnover that characterizes early growth. 
Several terms related to nicotinamide and pyridine nucleotide metabolism also appear, reflecting reduced activity in redox‑linked pathways that support rapid energy generation. 
The repeated enrichment of organophosphate and nucleoside diphosphate catabolic processes reinforces this pattern, showing a broad downshift in biosynthetic and catabolic functions tied to proliferation and metabolic flexibility. 
Together, these results suggest that as the biofilm transitions from early to thin, cells begin to scale back growth‑associated metabolism and shift toward a more resource‑limited, stress‑aware physiological state.

