GO Thin vs Mature downregulated genes
This plot shows a coordinated suppression of pathways that are active in the thin biofilm stage but become less important once the biofilm reaches full maturity. 
Many of the enriched categories relate to protein catabolism, including ubiquitin‑dependent and proteasome‑mediated degradation, indicating that thin biofilm cells rely more heavily on protein turnover and quality‑control mechanisms that are dialed back in the mature state. 
Additional terms tied to carbohydrate metabolism, energy generation, and energy‑reserve pathways suggest that thin biofilm cells maintain higher metabolic flexibility and energy‑producing activity, which declines as the mature biofilm adopts a more stable, resource‑conserving physiology. 
The presence of terms linked to morphogenesis and sporulation‑related processes further highlights that structural remodeling and developmental plasticity are reduced in the mature stage. 
Together, these themes show that mature biofilm cells downregulate metabolic, proteolytic, and morphogenetic programs that remain more active in thin biofilm, reflecting the transition from a dynamic intermediate state to a fully established, stress‑adapted velum.
